metadata.name: Isometric roulette #60
metadata.description:
A set of colorful cubes with a pseudo-random appearance thanks to some Perlin noise. This means diverse formations and (x, y, z) coordinates in a lot of different theming setups.

Each CLICK will trigger a random cube rearrangement based on the current edition that’s displayed, and trigger audio based on a selection of random chords and sound effects.

There are a total of 3 different types of sounds that are evenly distributed amongst the editions.

@computeremotions - 2022-10-03

metadata.name: unbuilt #135
metadata.description:
This is a journey through architecture that never existed.

Inspired by the grammatical rules behind French sacral architecture of the Middle Ages, this generative tool is meant for creating a collection of 256 plans of fictional buildings. Each plan is a unique variation on semantic relations between architectural elements: from a regular composition resembling existing churches to a dynamic aggregation of vaults, columns and chevets. But always following the same set of rules extracted from multiple examples of gothic cathedrals.

Every church has its place and time in which it could have been built in an alternative series of historical events.

This artistic tribute to the research of Stiny and Mitchell about Palladian architecture or Duarte's work about Siza takes the topic of formalizing architectural language onto a lighthearted level by moving it to a slightly imaginary world.

To zoom, press a mouse button when over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: The book of tender #30
metadata.description:
The book of tender is a book inspired in kintsugi, an ancient Japanese art technique based on repairing fractures from day-to-day objects, such as ceramics, using golden powder. The philosophy behind this practice, is that fractures and repairs are part of the history of an object. By evidencing them, an object can be perceived in its totality, in its history and transformation.

The book of tender is a book about caring where golden lines encounter the paper texture and in that process it showcases the beauty of healing and the fragility and power of transformation.

Press  from “1” to “9” to render at higher resolutions. If you choose higher resolutions you can follow the animation playing at slower rates.

Press “s” to save a .png file at the given resolution.

metadata.name: twofiftythousand #184
metadata.description:
twofiftythousand is about the chaos of unlimited decisions. Look for a pattern in the noise.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

Our skies in the next 30 years as temperatures are intensifying and we experience, in the present, unprecedent heat waves. 

Inspired in polaroid images. Each output represents an image, a collectible and a document of perpetual suns. 

Each image showcases a random date and time in the next 30 years.

Oftentimes we will see how the suns try to breach the borders of the polaroid. They seldom manage to completely invade the frame.

Press “s” to save a png image.
Press “h” to save a high resolution: 5500 x 3660 or 3660 x 5500 png frame.

metadata.name: Cozy Mess #27
metadata.description:
This work is based and built on a single palette that I assembled from "natural tones" make-up catalogs and colors.
Anything that promotes artificial means of seeking what's natural, is fascinating to me, so I tried different methods of mixing and blending these colors in a make-upish kind of way.
Although I only applied them to very flat -expanse like- surfaces, I think Mr. Dither did a pretty good job of binding both the technical and conceptual sides of the work.

metadata.name: Inland Emotions #248
metadata.description:
Inland Emotions

Over the centuries, ancient philosophers and modern psychologists have come to the same basic conclusion. The fact is that, according to a few millennia of research, there are a limited number of distinct human emotions, predefined by the human psyche. Sometimes it may seem like we are experiencing a "new" one, but on closer inspection, we see that it is the known emotions that are superimposed. Emotions are what they are, and they exist in the same way in each of us, whether we recognize them for what they are or not. But as our history blends into a new emerging state of the world, a whole new range of emotional responses are triggered within us. An infinite maelstrom of variations generated from a simple combination of a few emotions.


Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

Inland Emotions by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
